Reply-To: 20260314_233144_in_browser_text_to_speech_tts_is_achieved_using_the_web_speech_api_s_speechsynthesis_interface_wh

Yes, you can absolutely do this with Rust+WASM; you just can’t tap the browser’s built‑in TTS, so you need to synthesize digits yourself (e.g. formant or tiny wavetable) and then export the PCM to WAV. [wasmbyexample](https://wasmbyexample.dev/examples/reading-and-writing-audio/reading-and-writing-audio.rust.en-us)

## High‑level design

- Rust/WASM side: generate mono `Vec<f32>` PCM for the spoken digits at a fixed \(sample\_rate\). [cprimozic](https://cprimozic.net/blog/buliding-a-wavetable-synthesizer-with-rust-wasm-and-webaudio/)
- JS side:  
  - Turn that buffer into a WAV `Blob` (pure JS encoder).  
  - Optionally also shove it into a Web Audio `AudioBuffer` to preview playback. [docs](https://docs.rs/web-sys/latest/web_sys/struct.AudioContext.html)

I’ll give you a minimal pipeline with a dumb “robot voice” (per‑digit tones) so you can swap in a real synthesizer later.

***

## Rust (wasm‑bindgen) – generate PCM for digits

`Cargo.toml`:

```toml
[package]
name = "digit_tts"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[lib]
crate-type = ["cdylib"]

[dependencies]
wasm-bindgen = "0.2"
```

`src/lib.rs`:

```rust
use wasm_bindgen::prelude::*;

const SAMPLE_RATE: u32 = 16_000;

#[wasm_bindgen]
pub fn sample_rate() -> u32 {
    SAMPLE_RATE
}

/// Very crude "speak digits": each digit = 200ms of a tone at a different freq,
/// with 50ms silence between digits.
/// Returns a Vec<f32> that JS can see as Float32Array.
#[wasm_bindgen]
pub fn speak_digits(digits: &str) -> Vec<f32> {
    let mut samples = Vec::<f32>::new();

    let digit_freq = |d: char| -> f32 {
        match d {
            '0' => 300.0,
            '1' => 330.0,
            '2' => 360.0,
            '3' => 390.0,
            '4' => 420.0,
            '5' => 450.0,
            '6' => 480.0,
            '7' => 510.0,
            '8' => 540.0,
            '9' => 570.0,
            _ => 0.0,
        }
    };

    let tone_ms = 200.0;
    let gap_ms = 50.0;
    let tone_len = (SAMPLE_RATE as f32 * tone_ms / 1000.0) as usize;
    let gap_len = (SAMPLE_RATE as f32 * gap_ms / 1000.0) as usize;

    let mut t: f32 = 0.0;
    let dt: f32 = 1.0 / SAMPLE_RATE as f32;

    for ch in digits.chars() {
        let f = digit_freq(ch);
        if f <= 0.0 {
            // skip unknown chars, but still add gap
            samples.extend(std::iter::repeat(0.0).take(gap_len));
            continue;
        }

        // simple decaying sine for "digit"
        for _ in 0..tone_len {
            let env = 1.0; // plug an ADSR here if you care
            let s = (2.0 * std::f32::consts::PI * f * t).sin() * env * 0.4;
            samples.push(s);
            t += dt;
        }

        // gap
        samples.extend(std::iter::repeat(0.0).take(gap_len));
    }

    samples
}
```

Compile with `wasm-pack build --target web`. [rustwasm.github](https://rustwasm.github.io/docs/wasm-bindgen/print.html)

***

## JS – call WASM, encode to WAV, download

```js
import init, { speak_digits, sample_rate } from "./pkg/digit_tts.js";

function pcmToWav(pcm, sampleRate) {
  const numChannels = 1;
  const bytesPerSample = 2;
  const blockAlign = numChannels * bytesPerSample;
  const byteRate = sampleRate * blockAlign;
  const dataSize = pcm.length * bytesPerSample;
  const buffer = new ArrayBuffer(44 + dataSize);
  const view = new DataView(buffer);

  let offset = 0;
  const writeStr = (s) => {
    for (let i = 0; i < s.length; i++) {
      view.setUint8(offset++, s.charCodeAt(i));
    }
  };

  // RIFF header
  writeStr("RIFF");
  view.setUint32(offset, 36 + dataSize, true); offset += 4;
  writeStr("WAVE");

  // fmt chunk
  writeStr("fmt ");
  view.setUint32(offset, 16, true); offset += 4;     // chunk size
  view.setUint16(offset, 1, true); offset += 2;      // PCM
  view.setUint16(offset, numChannels, true); offset += 2;
  view.setUint32(offset, sampleRate, true); offset += 4;
  view.setUint32(offset, byteRate, true); offset += 4;
  view.setUint16(offset, blockAlign, true); offset += 2;
  view.setUint16(offset, 16, true); offset += 2;     // bits per sample

  // data chunk
  writeStr("data");
  view.setUint32(offset, dataSize, true); offset += 4;

  // samples
  for (let i = 0; i < pcm.length; i++) {
    let s = Math.max(-1, Math.min(1, pcm[i]));
    view.setInt16(
      offset,
      s < 0 ? s * 0x8000 : s * 0x7fff,
      true
    );
    offset += 2;
  }

  return new Blob([buffer], { type: "audio/wav" });
}

async function initTts() {
  await init(); // loads wasm

  window.makeDigitsWav = function (digits) {
    const sr = sample_rate();
    const pcm = speak_digits(digits); // Float32Array view of Vec<f32>

    const wavBlob = pcmToWav(pcm, sr);
    const url = URL.createObjectURL(wavBlob);

    const a = document.createElement("a");
    a.href = url;
    a.download = `digits_${digits}.wav`;
    a.click();

    URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
  };
}

initTts();
```

You can then call, e.g., from console or UI:

```js
makeDigitsWav("12345");
```

This will generate a WAV file in‑browser with a robotic tone sequence for “1 2 3 4 5.” [wasmbyexample](https://wasmbyexample.dev/examples/reading-and-writing-audio/reading-and-writing-audio.rust.en-us)

If you want something closer to Speak & Spell, the next step is to swap the “sine per digit” DSP with either:

- A small formant or LPC synth written in Rust and compiled to WASM, feeding into the same `Vec<f32>`; or  
- A little wavetable per digit (load small PCM snippets into WASM memory, concatenate, return). [github](https://github.com/PaulBatchelor/rust-wasm-audioworklet)

If you tell me which route you prefer (formant/LPC vs simple prerecorded digit samples), I can adapt the Rust side to that specifically.

